--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
 2. Pets can mess up positioning. Sometimes you can reposition just fine despite pets, sometimes you can't and that can mean a wipe.<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
<br>
In the case of repositioning, (I assume you mean moving from camp to camp during a raid) I will either leave my pet guarding in the original camp, then summon companion, or if for some reason that is not a good idea, reclaim the pet and recreate it at the new camp. So what if it costs extra mana; the raid is not about you. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is not what he means. <br>
<br>
Repositioning means, during a long fight, the mob can &quot;move&quot; out of position. In the case of certain fights (Griegs, Arryonar, etc) the mob needs to be in ONE place during the fight, and not get moved around, or pushed into a wall, or whatever... <br>
<br>
The reason positioning is important is for avoiding/managing AE spells, line of sight for the main tank, aggro control, and archery (for those rangers who have the AAX points to make it beneficial to use). <br>
<br>
Pets can totally screw this up. If the mob gets moved, the way to reposition is have everyone in melee range move away, and probably shut off attack too, and let the main tank with aggro reposition the mob. The problem with pets is, pets don't quit attacking. They just keep screwing up the positioning of the mob, and wipe the raid. <br>
<br>
<br>
I've seen it done, several times. Every time the solution is the same: remove pets from the equation. When this is done, the next time around it's a win instead of a wipeout. <br>
<br>
-Krazak<br>
